Topic 10:
Reproduction in Plants and Animals
Duration: 22 Periods
General Objective:
By the end of the topic the learner should be able to understand the mechanism by which living
organisms produce their off-springs and sustain their life on earth.
SUB-TOPIC
PERIOD SPECIFIC OBJECTIVE
CONTENT
.
10.1 Asexual
Reproduction
in lower
organisms
Define asexual reproduction.
Describe binary fission in
amoeba
Describe the structure of
mucor.
Explain how mucor
reproduces through
sporulation
Describe budding in yeast.
Explain how spirogyra
reproduces by fragmentation.
Conduct a practical on
growth of of mucor /
rhizopus on moist bread.
Asexual reproduction
in amoeba and
mucor/thizopus.
Budding in yeast
Fragmentation in
spirogyra.
Practical activity on
growth of mucor or
rhizopus.
TEACHING AND LEARNING
STRATEGIES
Discussion on a sexual
reproduction in lower
organisms.
Demonstration on budding in
yeast and fragmentation in
spirogyra.
Practical on growth of mucor or
rhizopus using moist bread,
10.2 Asexual
Reproduction in
plants (vegetative
reproduction)
Define vegetative
reproduction
List plant structures used in
vegetative reproduction.
Explain vegetative
reproduction using leaves of
Bryophyllum.
Describe structure of a stem
tuber and a bulb.
Draw and label parts of a
sucker and rhizome.
Concept of vegetative
reproduction in plants
Stem tubers and bulbs
Suckers and rhizomes
and their parts.
Corms and its parts.
Differences between a
rhizome and corm
Practical activity on
drawing and labeling
of vegetative parts.
Discuss vegetative reproduction
in plants.
Guided discussion and
explanation on stern tubes,
bulbs, suckers, rhizomes and
corms.
Brain storm on advantages and
disadvantages of vegetative
reproduction

Topic 10:


Reproduction in Plants and Animals


Duration: 22 Periods


General Objective:


By the end of the topic the learner should be able to understand the mechanism by which living organisms produce their off-springs and sustain their life on earth.


SUB-TOPIC


PERIOD SPECIFIC OBJECTIVE


CONTENT


.


10.1 Asexual
Reproduction in lower organisms


Define asexual reproduction. Describe binary fission in amoeba Describe the structure of mucor. Explain how mucor reproduces through sporulation Describe budding in yeast. Explain how spirogyra reproduces by fragmentation. Conduct a practical on growth of of mucor / rhizopus on moist bread.


Asexual reproduction in amoeba and mucor/thizopus. Budding in yeast Fragmentation in spirogyra. Practical activity on growth of mucor or rhizopus.


TEACHING AND LEARNING STRATEGIES
Discussion on a sexual reproduction in lower organisms. Demonstration on budding in yeast and fragmentation in spirogyra. Practical on growth of mucor or rhizopus using moist bread,


10.2 Asexual Reproduction in plants (vegetative reproduction)


Define vegetative reproduction List plant structures used in vegetative reproduction. Explain vegetative reproduction using leaves of Bryophyllum. Describe structure of a stem tuber and a bulb. Draw and label parts of a sucker and rhizome.


Concept of vegetative reproduction in plants Stem tubers and bulbs Suckers and rhizomes and their parts. Corms and its parts. Differences between a rhizome and corm Practical activity on drawing and labeling of vegetative parts.


Discuss vegetative reproduction in plants. Guided discussion and explanation on stern tubes, bulbs, suckers, rhizomes and corms. Brain storm on advantages and disadvantages of vegetative reproduction
